[According to an update of this report, WHO's Dr Michael Ryan, who is directing the agency's Ebola response, said 30 contacts in the Goma case had already been vaccinated and the remaining 30 would be vaccinated on Tuesday [16 Jul 2019].

The pastor was transferred back to Butembo on Monday [15 Jul 2019] in accordance with a decision by Congo's Ministry of Health, according to Doctors Without Borders, which runs the Ebola clinic in Goma where he was diagnosed. (Note that the pastor died during transport.)

WHO and partners have also said the response has been hampered by a lack of resources, repeatedly citing a USD 50 million gap in its Ebola containment plan. "Unless there's a big scale-up in the (funding) response, we're unlikely to be successful in getting to zero cases," UN emergency relief coordinator Mark Lowcock said.

On Monday [15 Jul 2019], Rory Stewart, Britain's secretary of state for international development, announced the UK would donate another USD 63 million to help stop the outbreak. He also called for other G7 countries to increase their support, specifically Francophone countries.

If people refuse to follow directives from those trying to control virus spread, this outbreak is likely to simmer along with the threat of explosion for a very long time. - Mod.LK]

- Tue 16 Jul 2019. Rwanda
[provinces26rdc.net, in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.provinces26rdc.net/ebola-le-rwanda-demande-deviter-les-voyages-au-congo/

The Rwandan Ministry of Health on Monday [15 Jul 2019] urged its nationals to avoid any trip to eastern DRC after the discovery of an Ebola case in Goma, a city close to the border between the 2 countries. This case was discovered in Goma, a city of one million people separated by the border of the city of Gisenyi, in western Rwanda. The crossing of the border between Goma and Gisenyi is one of the most used in the region: Thousands of people use it every day. Although no Ebola case has been reported in Rwanda, it is vital that Rwandans take action to help prevent the spread of Ebola, the ministry said.

"The Ministry of Health reminds citizens and residents not to cross the border for unnecessary travel to areas in neighboring countries where Ebola cases have been reported," stressed the ministry. And to add: "We recommend that our citizens and residents not provide accommodation to travelers who come from areas of neighboring countries where Ebola has been reported."

