This is an important and insightful editorial on how best to manage Ebola outbreaks. It is absolutely true that strong public health infrastructure will always provide the best defense against outbreaks of Ebola and other important diseases such as malaria, cholera, measles, TB, and more. However, it is incumbent on the community to take advantage of the facilities and expertise that exists, and this takes education and trust. No matter how well equipped are the facilities and how well prepared are the healthcare workers, sick individuals must present themselves to the clinics to be cared for. In some locations, that may be harder to develop than a strong public health infrastructure. For example, a modelling study suggested that 3% of people with Ebola infected more than 60% of all cases during the 2014-2015 West African epidemic. These "superspreaders" -- the very old or very young, who stayed at home rather than attend a treatment centre -- fuelled the outbreak's growth and prolonged its duration. (see Lau MSY, Dalziel BD, Funk S, et al. Spatial and temporal dynamics of superspreading events in the 2014-2015 West Africa Ebola epidemic. PNAS 2017;114(9):2337-42. https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1614595114).

Nonetheless, a goal of access by everyone to clean running water and soap would be a great start. - Mod.LK

